5. Applied Regression III

2023-02-28

Back to content page

Learning objectives

  • Identify and handle multicollinearity
  • Account for confounding factors in regression model
  • Assess potential effect modifiers in regression model
  • Perform basic mediation analysis

1 Multicollinearity

  • Collinearity = strong linear dependency/high correlation between two predictor variables (X1 and X2)
    • Collinear variables give similar information, e.g.personal income and household income
    • For perfect collinearity between two predictor variables X1 and X2. We can find constants a, b so that \(X_1 = a + bX_2\) , e.g.X1 = degree in Celsius, X2 = degree in Fahrenheit
  • Multicollinearity: Predictor variable strongly depends on other predictor variables linearly, e.g.X4 = a + b1X1 + b2X2 + b3X3 has a very good fit
  • Multicollinearity does not violate any of the assumptions of linear regression model BUT
    • e.g.for perfectly correlated predictors \(X_1 = a + bX_2\)
    • \(Y = + _1X_1 + _2X_2 = ( + a_1) + (b_1 + _2)X_2\).
    • We can always find different sets of (, 1, 2) to represent exactly the same relation > inflates standard error of the estimated coefficients > Uncertainty in estimated coefficients is large

Example: MVC

  • Suppose we create a new variable height.sq which is the square of the heights
  • We fit the linear regression model including height.sq:
mvc <- read.csv("Folder/mvc.csv")
mvc$height.sq <- mvc$height^2 #create a new variable
pairs(mvc) #We can see taht height and height.sq is highly correlated (45 degree line)

summary(lm(MVC~age+height, data=mvc)) #Standard error is 2.545
summary(lm(MVC~age+height+height.sq, data=mvc)) #If we have multicollinearity, the standard error become very big (127.8036)

1.1 Diagnostics

  • For pairwise collinearity, use scatterplot to plot between all predictor variables
  • For multicollinearity, use Variance inflation factor (VIF) require the car package vif(model)
    • VIFj = 1 / (1 Rj2) where Rj2 is the R2 when predictor Xj is regressed on all other predictors (e.g., R2 when X1 is regressed on X2, X3, X4) > when Rj2 is large (have collinearity), VIF is very large
    • Threshold: VIF > 10 = potential multicollinearity problem
require(car)
mvc.lm3 <- lm(MVC~age+height+height.sq, data=mvc)
vif(mvc.lm3) #Very large VIF for the height terms --> multicollinearity
##         age      height   height.sq 
##    1.140494 2788.043855 2784.139173

1.2 Solution

  • Do nothing coz estimated coefficients are still unbiased
    • But be careful coz inefficient estimation (very big standard error) Affect the main objectives of the analysis?
  • In practice
    1. Increase the sample size at planning stage
    2. Centering (only for polynomial terms and interactions, doesnt help other collinearity problem)
      Subtract the mean values from the variable (i.e. \(X \rightarrow X - \overline{X}\) or \(X^{2} \rightarrow (X - \overline{X})^{2}\) )
      scale (x, scale=F)
      1. x is the centered object
      2. scale = T: x is divided by standard deviations (but no need this so we set it as F)
    3. Drop one or more variables causing multicollinearity
      Most appropriate when two variables basically measure the same thing Problematic if the variable is an important confounder
##Centering
mvc$ct.height <- scale(mvc$height, scale=F) #Generate centered height
mvc$ct.height.sq <- mvc$ct.height^2 #Generate centered height square
mvc.lm4 <- lm(MVC~age+ct.height+ct.height.sq, data=mvc)
vif(mvc.lm4) #VIF is much lower after centering
##          age    ct.height ct.height.sq 
##     1.140494     1.603104     1.534462
#Note that R2 is the same as before coz we just transform the variables

Other potential problems in regression models

  1. Multilevel structure
    E.g., correlation within hospital or ward (Patients in the same ward will be similar)
    Need to fit multi-level models to account for multilevel structure
  2. Measurement error
    Imprecise measurement in predictors will attenuate estimated coefficients toward zero (close to null value) > need to be careful

2 Confounding

Example: Cardiovascular risk in the elderly

  • 1000 subjects aged 60-90y
  • Variables
    • sfrs: standardized Framingham risk score (10y cardiovascular risk)
    • phy: physical activity index, 0100 (high)
    • ses: social economic status, 010 (high)
    • age, bmi, male
  • Study objective: Assess the effect of physical activity on 10y cardiovascular risk

require(readxl)
cardio <- read_excel("Folder/cardio.xlsx")

Minimizing confounding

  • Need priori subject-matter knowledge of the causal structure
  1. Automatic variable selection Based on p-values of the variables OR AIC
  2. Relative change in estimate greater than 10% > classify it as confounder
  3. Standard rules for confounding:
    • Check if C is associated with E
    • Check if C is associated with D
    • Check if C does not lie in the causal pathway between E and D

2.1 Automatic variable selection

  1. Start with a model with full set or subset of variables
    • Must include exposure and outcome variables
    • May include higher order terms (e.g.interaction or polynomial terms like height^2)
  2. In each step, add a single term from all variables or drop a term in current model
  3. Compare AIC/p value for each model
  4. Repeat until theres no more changes

stepAIC(model)

require(MASS)
cf2 <- lm(sfrs~phy+ses, data=cardio)
stepAIC(cf2) #first model lowest AIC (-789.42) so stick with first model
## Start:  AIC=-789.42
## sfrs ~ phy + ses
## 
##        Df Sum of Sq    RSS     AIC

## lm(formula = sfrs ~ phy + ses, data = cardio)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)          phy          ses  
##     1.40997     -0.04454      0.14191
  • Problem: overfitting of data, multiple testing incorrect P-value
  • Stepwise methods include forward, backward, or combined. In practice, its better to start with variables we r interested then do backward selection.

2.2 Relative change in estimate

old <- coef(lm(sfrs~phy, data=cardio))[2]
new <- coef(lm(sfrs~phy+ses, data=cardio)) [2]
(new-old)/old*100 #percentage change = 28% > 10% so ses is confounder

new2 <- coef(lm(sfrs~phy+age, data=cardio)) [2]
(new2-old)/old*100 #percentage change = 7% < 10% so age is not confounder
##      phy 
## 27.99171 
##       phy 
## 0.7108784

2.3 Standard rule

summary(lm(phy~ses, data=cardio)) #statistically significant
summary(lm(sfrs~ses, data=cardio)) #statistically significant
#ses does not lie in the casual pathway between phy and sfrs

3. Effect modification

  • Effect of exposure on outcome modified by a third factor = effect modifier
    • To identify population subgroups with higher (synergism) or lower (antagonism) from intervention
    • Can be evaluated by
      • Stratified analysis
      • Fitting regression model with an interaction term

Example: Cardiovascular risk in the elderly

Suppose age is a potential effect modifier of the phy effect on sfrs

age.int <- lm(sfrs~phy*age+ses, data=cardio)
summary(age.int)

4. Mediation

  • To understand the mechanism of the exposure
  • Mediation effect: when mediator carries the effect of the exposure
    1. to outcome (Y)
    • Full mediation: direct effect = 0
    • Partial mediation: direct effect 0

Example: Cardiovascular risk in the elderly

Suppose bmi is a potential mediator of the phy effect on sfrs

4.1 Baron and Kenny criteria

  • Is exposure associated with the mediator? (M~E)
  • Is mediator associated with the outcome? (Y~M)
  • Is exposure associated with the outcome? (Y~E)
  • Does adjusting for the mediator reduce the association between the exposure and the outcome (attenuation) (compare with Y~E+M)
    • Note that the criteria is only valid in some simple situations but is not always valid (discussed in CMED6030)
summary(lm(bmi~phy, data=cardio)) # = -0.096, p < 0.001
summary(lm(sfrs~bmi, data=cardio)) # = -0.009, p = 0.130
summary(lm(sfrs~phy, data=cardio)) #phy = -0.035, p < 0.001
summary(lm(sfrs~phy+bmi, data=cardio)) #phy = -0.041, p < 0.001 (no attenuation)
##BMI doesn't satisfy 2nd and 4th B&K criterion.

4.2 Sobel test

  • The indirect effect is =
  • Null hypothesis H0 of sobel test = 0. Can generate z value
    • \(z = \frac {} {\sqrt{^2^2_ + ^2^2_}}\) (denominator is sd of )
      • is obtained by fitting M~E
      • is obtained by fitting Y~E+M
    • It is a mediator if significance level <5% (z > 1.96)
    • Note:
      • Other versions of Sobel-Goodman test have different forms of the denominator
      • This is for continuous outcomes. A more complicated version is needed for binary outcomes
  • sobel(iv, mv, dv) (in package: multilevel)
    • iv is the independent variable (E)
    • mv is the mediator variable (M)
    • dv is the dependent variable (Y)

require("multilevel")
out <- with(cardio, sobel(phy, bmi, sfrs)) #(with function: use cardio dataset)
2*pnorm(out$z.value, lower.tail=F) #2* to find 2-sided p value; lower.tail=F to find P[X>x] otherwise is P[Xx].
## [1] 5.466551e-23
## 2 tail pval = 5.466551e-23 < 0.05 => Reject H0. There is significant mediation effect
##Self-practice, use sobel test without the package
m1 <- lm(bmi~phy, data=cardio)
m2 <- lm(sfrs~phy+bmi, data=cardio)
summary (m1)
summary (m2)

 <- coef(m1) [2]
sd <- coef(summary(m1)) [2,2]
 <- coef(m2) [3]
sd <- coef(summary(m2)) [3,2]
z <- * / sqrt(^2*sd^2 + ^2*sd^2)
2*pnorm(z, lower.tail=F)

Some comments on Sobel test

  • Usually regarded as more accurate than Baron and Kenny criteria
  • Need large sample size
    • for smaller sample size the normal assumption for the test statistics may not be valid
    • could be handled by bootstrapping (will be covered in CMED6040)
  • May also need to adjust for confounding (depending on the causal structure)
    • Functions like mediation.test do not consider other confounders
